Orchestrate ticket(s) {{arg}} through the full lifecycle — describe → execute → review → fix → merge — using sub-agents for the heavy phases while you, the orchestrator, keep every backend write.

**Argument guard.** The ticket list is `{{arg}}`. Every whitespace-separated token must be a well-formed ticket id — {{#if project.ticketPrefix}}`{{upper project.ticketPrefix}}-<number>`{{else}}`<PREFIX>-<number>` (e.g. `{{eg.prefixUpper}}-312`){{/if}}. Drop anything else (words, paths, stray dashes) and recover the intended ids from the invocation text or conversation; state which ids you recovered and repeat them in the final message so the user can catch a wrong guess. If several ids are plausible, or none can be recovered, ask the user with the candidate ids displayed. A malformed id must never reach backend calls, branch names, or commit messages.

{{> delegation}}

## Model split

Which model runs each role is a cost/quality decision the operator owns — never resolve it silently. Resolution order: **explicit per-run instruction > config > ask**.

- **Per-run override.** A model split the user states in the invocation or the conversation wins over everything below, configured values included. It applies to this run only and skips any model-split question; it is never written back to config, and the kickoff summary must flag it as a one-run override.
{{#if (and orchestrate.plannerModel orchestrate.implementerModel)}}
- **Configured split.** This project pins both roles in config — Planner: `{{orchestrate.plannerModel}}`, Implementer: `{{orchestrate.implementerModel}}`. Absent a per-run instruction, use it without asking.
{{else}}
- **Ask first.** No configured split — before any phase work, {{ask "which model split to use for this run — **Split** (recommended): the strongest model plans and reviews, the worker model builds and fixes; **All-strongest**: the strongest model for both roles; **Budget**: the worker model for both roles; **Custom**: name a model per role, with optional per-phase overrides"}}. Do not proceed until the user has answered.
{{/if}}
- **Pin on spawn.** Pin the resolved model on each sub-agent spawn where your tool supports it; otherwise record the chosen split in the sub-agent brief and the kickoff summary and proceed.
- **Kickoff summary.** Open the run by naming the resolved split and where it came from (per-run instruction, config, or the user's answer). The kickoff summary and every boundary summary must name which model ran each phase.
- **Persist offer.** When the run's split is not already pinned in config, offer to save it to the `orchestrate` config block only **after the run completes** — at the final boundary summary, back on the base branch. Never edit the config mid-run, and never write the choice back silently.

## Roles

- **Planner** — plans and reviews; runs on the Planner model resolved above. Owns the describe-phase analysis and the review-phase findings.
- **Implementer** — builds and fixes; runs on the Implementer model resolved above. Owns code, tests, and commits on the ticket branch.
- **You (orchestrator)** — sequencing, every {{backend.displayName}} write (with receipts), git/PR operations, and all user interaction.

## Sub-agent briefs

Sub-agent prompts must embed the relevant phase skill's procedure — read the phase skill file and carry its instructions verbatim where the sub-agent needs them; sub-agents return their results as data. Every brief must:

- Point at the finalized plan artifact and the user-ratified decisions, stating explicitly that those decisions **override** the raw ticket text where they differ.
- State the scope boundary — what belongs to this ticket's PR vs later tickets — and that sub-agents never push, open PRs, or write to the ticket backend.
- State the gates and exact baselines (e.g. the test count to beat) and the commit conventions.
- Require a structured return: per-task status, files touched, final gate numbers, deviations, commit SHAs, unresolved forks.
- Instruct stop-and-return on a genuine product fork — a sub-agent can never reach the user.

## Interaction contract

Exactly two classes of questions reach the user **mid-run** (the model-split resolution above and the persist offer sit outside it, at the run's open and close); everything else runs autonomously:

1. **Product clarifications and plan ratification** during planning (describe's clarifying questions — batch them per ticket; then the plan ratification STOP); the bubbled message itself must display the Planner's summary, user stories, and acceptance criteria — sub-agent output is invisible to the user unless you relay it.
2. **Judgment calls on review findings** (fix now / skip / defer — present the Planner's findings grouped, with your recommendation).

Hard gates still stop the run regardless: a failing test gate, merge confirmation, destructive actions, and anything the phase skills mark "stop and ask".

## Ordering

Fetch every ticket up front ({{op "getTicket"}} for each id — this doubles as the backend preflight; if the tool is missing or erroring, stop and tell the user). Resolve the dependency order: `Blocked-by` relations and description chains. A blocked ticket waits until its blocker is **merged**, not merely built. Escape hatch: if the blocker's merge is held by something external (e.g. a deploy prerequisite) and the user approves, stack — branch the next ticket off the blocker's branch and keep building; once the blocker merges, rebase onto the base branch (`git rebase --onto origin/{{git.baseBranch}} <old-base>`) and retarget the PR. Work strictly one phase of one ticket at a time; do not interleave phases across tickets.

## Per ticket — the standard lifecycle, delegated

Each ticket gets its own artifact, branch, and state transitions — never shared, never skipped.

1. **Plan (Planner).** The Planner returns product behavior, user stories, acceptance criteria, clarifying questions, and a draft test-driven plan as data. Bubble the clarifying questions to the user (STOP class 1): {{ask "the Planner's clarifying questions" context="the Planner's summary, user stories, and acceptance criteria, plus the clarifying questions themselves"}} After answers, the Planner finalizes the plan; then display the refined user stories and the execution plan and STOP for the user to ratify them (no trivial-clarifications escape). Only after ratification do **you** write the work artifact with `status: planning` — {{> artifact-write}} — and check out the ticket branch per `/describe-ticket`.
2. **Build (Implementer).** First the build-start gate from `/execute-ticket`: artifact to `status: building`, then {{op "setState" state="inProgress"}}. Only then spawn the Implementer on the ticket branch; it works the plan test-first and returns commits + test results as data. **You** run the test gate, push, open the PR — verifying independently: re-run the full test gate on the exact tip being pushed (never trust the Implementer's reported numbers alone) and confirm a clean tree — then complete `/execute-ticket` step 5: attach the PR, post the shipping note, move to {{state "inReview"}}, update the artifact.
3. **Review (Planner).** The Planner reviews the PR against the acceptance criteria and returns a verdict + findings as data. **You** record the review comment and the artifact's `Review verdict` per `/review-ticket`, then bubble the blocking findings to the user (STOP class 2). Findings the user defers go to **one deferred-findings ticket for the whole batch** — create it on first use ({{op "createTicket"}}), number findings sequentially as they accumulate, and reference it from each PR body, so nothing is lost and nothing blocks.
4. **Fix loop (Implementer).** For the findings the user accepted, run the `/fix-ticket` procedure with the Implementer doing the code work; re-review with the Planner until the verdict is ✅. After fixes, the Planner **spot-verifies each applied fix** — it resolves its finding, introduces no new bug or regression, and breaks no interface a downstream ticket depends on — before re-review concludes.
5. **Merge.** Confirm with the user, then follow `/merge-ticket`: review gate, merge, closing comment, done state, artifact `status: merged`, cleanup. Before merging, watch CI to completion and read each check's conclusion individually — never trust a watcher's exit code alone. When the user has granted standing merge authority, distinguish dormant from live: a flag-gated change that deploys inert may merge without a fresh confirm; a change that alters live production behavior always gets an explicit confirm plus a prerequisites checklist in the PR body.
6. **Boundary summary.** Before starting the next ticket, report: ticket → PR → verdict → state, with receipts (comment ids / URLs) and the model that ran each phase.

{{> checkpoint next="start any phase of the next ticket" require="the previous phase's backend writes are receipted on the current ticket"}}

## Resume / idempotency

Re-running with the same ticket list resumes each ticket from its artifact `status` (planning → building → in-review → merged) — never redo a receipted phase, never post a duplicate artifact.
